A black box in your car?
While U.S. road planners are struggling to find the money to repair the decaying highway infrastructure, many are seeing a solution in the form of a small black box that hangs over the dashboard of your car.
The devices, which record every mile a driver travels and transmit information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and government planning offices to overhaul the outdated system of funding major U.S. roads.
The generally uninteresting area of broad-based planning has suddenly provoked a lively debate and unrestricted alliances.
Liberals have joined environmental groups to push for the government to use the little boxes to track the miles you're traveling, and possibly the road you're driving, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party is landing.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses concern about the protection of privacy.
And while members of Congress can't agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They're looking at how, over the next decade, they can move to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental ride.
This is really essential for our nation.
 It's not like we had a choice , said Hasan Ikhrata, general manager of the Southern California Association of Governments, which predicts that the state will start recording the miles traveled by every California driver by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, funded by taxes Americans pay on the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars can travel more than a mile with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents a gallon, hasn't been raised in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax even by a hundred, when gasoline prices are high.
 The gas tax is simply not sustainable , said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed tracking devices on 500 cars to test a mileage system.
 This turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long term , he said.
Wonks calls this mileage usage fee.
It is not surprising that the idea appeals to city liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits in order to reduce congestion and emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set out in the state's ambitious climate change laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-PA), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also considered it the most viable long-term alternative.
The free market supporters of the Reason Foundation also appreciate the idea of paying drivers per mile.
 This is not just a tax that is clogging itself in a big black hole , said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transportation Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go the mile-pay path.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot last year that would have involved about 10,000 cars.
But the House presidency killed the proposal, responding to concerns from rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to work or the city.
However, several states and major cities are making progress on their own.
The most determined is Oregon, which mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the nation's most important experiment.
These drivers will soon be paying the state for miles instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transportation in states along the U.S. East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida) is looking at how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer drivers recently equipped their cars with a machine, drivers were concerned that the government could track their every move.
 Concerns about Big Brother and stuff like that are a big problem , said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the beginning of the trial, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website:  It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into fully localized devices. 
There is no need to build a huge, overwhelming technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's daily comings and goings.
