George Kerevan: The break-up of Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another disturbing story of independence.
This time, we are being warned that an independent Scotland would have to join the European free movement zone to join the EU.
And now we hear stories of passport control in Berwick and a border of barbed wire along Hadrian's Wall.
While it is true that the Strathclyde newspaper reported the possible economic consequences of greater freedom of movement with the rest of Europe, this was not in the headlines (and was to be expected).
Nor did anyone say that EU Member States spend much of their time bypassing their formal rules when it suits them.
Since Scotland is not part of the Schengen area at the moment, a continued non-compliance with the rules would be a small concession that Brussels could offer in return for anything it wants from Scots.
So this is not a story.
And a story so old that it's now frozen: I first heard the gossip that  independence means passport control over 40 years ago.
Yet, we have forgotten an interesting point in this interpretation of an old dust tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow Europe's instructions, in fact?
Why trade the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
The real news about Europe is this: the postwar plan to unite Europe is definitely deadlocked.
With the euro crisis, the Europe Project is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties opposed to the EU or advocating the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and coming out of nowhere, gathered almost five million votes in the federal elections in September and pulled the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the proposal to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the burden on national economies through accession to the single currency, has led many to believe that the Europe Project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits  this was only true for Greece.
The European system has instead imposed favourable exchange rates on its members for German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the national currency, the countries of southern Europe are left with an inherent productivity problem vis-à-vis Germany.
The only way forward is to make the grim cuts in wages and public spending encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current budgetary and monetary problems, there is a deeper discomfort in productivity in Europe.
Following the green energy policies imposed by Brussels which are a reason to subsidise French and German energy companies at consumer expense, European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than the United States.
This is a cost-effective re-publication disadvantage, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
All the world's wage gains will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap US shale gas.
As a result, the revolt has been one of the major drivers of the EU, particularly in France.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport for its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the French economy in a state of disrepair.
The result: Marine Le Pen's far-right party, the anti-European Front National, has just won a crucial by-election, putting the Socialists in power back in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote  a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot start on the principle that a split of the right will automatically favour the left.
What is Marine Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among the French white working class?
It wants to use the European elections next year to create a single anti-money and anti-European bloc within the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties are successful in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, the anti-European and anti-monetary sentiment in Europe will unite and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something more like the free Europe of Nations (sovereign) privileged by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will have their own currency.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will be mildly appreciated by the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of small England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending people around Berlin and Brussels.
I believe that Scotland could settle for a freer European agreement provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of Nations.
Otherwise, we should be following Norway's example and maintaining our economic independence.
The Scottish SNP government is  and it is worth noting  the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, having won a dramatic majority in 2011 based on its opposition to the dark cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling and the Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition that followed.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to vote for independence if it were to accept the austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: Early aging
Studies show that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
Changes in body shape do not mean puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe the obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The tendency to puberty early is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother worry if her daughter's breasts and pubic hair start growing at seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American youth and represent a new norm.
 I spend a lot of time reassuring parents  in general, this does not indicate a rapid development towards full puberty , Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as swollen breasts, hair under the arms and pubic area, and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance from the age of first menstruation over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half, up from 12 in 1970.
 Once the breast has started to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first menstrual period appears , said Kaplowitz, also the author of  Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem .
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will develop.
There is debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered to be early when the breast develops with sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows or stops  this is something a pediatrician can follow closely.
A faster progression may warrant tests by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first period and prevent other consequences: premature bone ageing that can slow growth and a small height in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormone treatment are based on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about medications but acknowledges that  controlling puberty can alleviate certain behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others 
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young daughters to have their period.
 They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues , Kaplowitz said.
 It was a shock , remembers a woman whose daughter had her first period at the age of 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about the rules, she wasn't emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset about being the first of her friends.
There are many theories that have been made public about the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that the hormones in milk or other foods, the chemicals in the environment, or the sexual messages carried by the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz says the most credible hypothesis is the obesity epidemic.
He was involved in a study of girls aged 6 to 9 years that linked the percentage of fat mass to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Worldwide, the mechanisms of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have hair on their faces and in the pubic area younger, the tendency toward true early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference stressed the complexity of the subject.
Acne and pubic hair are common, even in infants and toddlers.
 We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty , said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at the Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their pediatrician about how to communicate with their children.
 This may mean having a conversation earlier than planned , Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will respond well.
Girls who are in early puberty need to be reassured that even when it happens earlier than expected, the process is part of life.
