They're not supposed to turn them on again until the plane reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gives his green light.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their devices when the aircraft descends before landing and not turn them on again until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during takeoffs, landings and ground rolling, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft which have been modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
