Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said that cell phones were still considered a risk.
 Mobile phones are a real problem, not only because they could potentially create interference with navigation instruments, but because we know, according to the FCC, that they could disrupt mobile phone radio antennas if used on board , Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to look into the issue last month recommended that the government allow for wider use of personal electronic devices.
The pressure on the FAA has increased in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there is no valid security reason for these bans.
Restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least one third of passengers forget to turn off their appliances, or do so deliberately.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers carried FM radios, the high-tech gadget of the time.
The new airliners rely much more on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic interference and are FAA-approved.
Airlines have been allowing passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruise altitudes for several years.
Airplanes modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems also resist interference better.
