How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Did he run out of passwords to type in to access his smartphone or pay for his purchases?
American, French, or Japanese researchers predict a future where we'll be recognized by biometric sensors on phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Deputy Director General of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person conducting transactions in a transversal and transnational universe such as the Internet.
Privacy organizations confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 alone and in France, the National Commission for Information and Freedom authorised 774 fingerprint recognition systems, hand shape or hand vein network in businesses, government departments, canteens...
"Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime", says Justin Brookman, consumer privacy officer at the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT), in Washington.
What are the reasons for such optimism in some and pessimism in others?
Biometrics will be based on new technologies, which will enable new services to be provided to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its limitations.
"For example, some people who work on concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable", observes Philippe Robin, technical director of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection and checking of the vein and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the person.
This is both a security - you cannot capture this data without them - and a disadvantage: the procedure sometimes has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for some twenty years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
The increased precision of sensors and the computational capacity of computers required for data analysis make these techniques operational.
Facial recognition accuracy has increased tenfold over the past five years, says Cyrille Bataller, Accenture's director of R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today we are doing research on voice recognition or walking using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment", says Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
DNA is a unique and unmistakable marker, and it also raises hopes and concerns.
"At the current level of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data", confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospects at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police a suitcase of 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and within an hour.
The uses of biometrics fall into two groups: identification (recognition of a person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who he claims to be).
Identification has hitherto been concerned with the issue of identity papers: biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) must be compared with the information the State has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that one person does not attempt to steal someone else's identity.
This comparison principle may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
"We take the images from the surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of celebrities who are freely circulating on the Internet", explains Dany Nassif, head of commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Another use: to photograph a quidam queuing in a store, to track its progress by facial recognition and to calculate the waiting time.
Authentication was originally concerned with physical access (border, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
The presence control has been added to this recently.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of a friend pointing for another", explains Cyrille Bataller of Accenture.
But increasingly, authentication will also involve transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing a card and placing your hand on a biometric reader.
A similar technique is being tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in stores with their bank card, the customer does not type his code but inserts his finger into a vein-scanning reader.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon be available to French merchants.
Ways to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the cash for 30 seconds less, it is appreciated", explains the manager of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: within a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you customized options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people's identities are on a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which locks if you try to move it", says Philippe Robin de Thales.
But because of the lack of detailed studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy experts, on the other hand, continue to worry.
"The advances in facial recognition, the proliferation of surveillance cameras and the huge number of photos available on Facebook, Flickr and Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance", predicts Andrew Patrick, of the Canadian Privacy Commissioner's Office.
