Scientists have just shed light on how a dog's tail movements are linked to his mood.
Previous studies have shown that happy dogs tend to move their tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs tend to move their tail more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said:  Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in the stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions. 
Here we tried to see what was happening in other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain was responsible for left-hand movement and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the animals' heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
It will probably be a while before we understand why their tail sometimes goes one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained:  We showed dogs films with other dogs  either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion  and we were able to manipulate the tail movement and present it as moving to the left or right. 
When the animals saw a dog without an expression move its tail to the right (from the dog's point of view), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail that was mostly turned left (again from the dog's point of view), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs communicated with each other deliberately through these movements.
Rather, he thinks dogs know by experience what movements they should or should not worry about.
He added:  If you meet other dogs repeatedly and notice that, most of the time, the tail movement to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to that experience. 
The researchers say the findings could help owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their pets' emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Sciences, said that this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said:  Dogs were more likely to go to a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than the right, instead of becoming anxious  the opposite of what the Italian study shows. 
He said the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not fully consider the animals in the movies or the robot dogs as dogs.
He explained that a study of how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful.
 Although many evidence from different mammals indicates that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details are still to be clarified  and dogs are no exception , he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it will likely take us a while to understand why their tail moves sometimes one way and sometimes the other.
