Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents her two new group choreographies at Danse Danse: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by Satie's famous piano solos Gymnopédies.
A night that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and black ink to white.
A white screen serves as a wall of background.
On the carpet, so white, in the vast space that is the Maisonneuve Theatre, stands, profile, fine as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, a simple trait, takes shape.
And this shape will be the shape of the whole room: a bunch of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, with only their hands and face uncovered, wait on either side of the playground, rush out when the next graphic appears, embody it, run out.
This black and white play by Henri Michaux is performed in solo relay, in a group unison (a mass that does solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
We think of "Morning Glory", where Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on posters, put online at the front of the stage.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur will take refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux's poem, monochorded and monotonous in the chorus, and will continue dancing.
And the music of going back, and the sequence of going back.
This long, energetic, loud discharge, if possible, eventually deafens and numbs.
And so does the regularity of visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes -- creating images has always been a strength at Chouinard -- like those hair that grow out or those black fabrics that stretch the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
It seems that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has imposed herself with her tics.
The result is that the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux's inks, like Gestalt forms, open up a wider, more giant imagination than dance, more porous.
Only the ending, in the negative, with its dancers cut by a stroboscopic light and the white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches the magic.
The audience liked it, and the reception was warm.
Gymnopedies, after the interact, are richer.
The stage is partially grey, the dancers and a piano are covered in fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
On the piano, dancers take turns playing the notes.
Their touching, uncomfortable music gives them a real fragility.
On stage, couples are paired in a romantic, very sensual, even erotic, duo.
Group work, little solo transitions, moving ensembles, choirs, writing is less binary.
The same buffalo, familiar to Chouinard, appear with a red nose in a highly polarized male-female love parade.
Love is a carnival, a fugitive, a gambler.
The gestures, the laughter and the small screams are a beautiful transition to the archaic, graceful and ridiculous of the coitus bodies of the melting creatures.
But the play takes its real flight after the rescue.
A clown comes back on stage when the audience leaves.
There everything is allowed: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes overlap, the dancers co-operate, descend among the spectators, glosses, smokes, short-circuits, codes of applause, and stretch the sauce into a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness sweat, and it's Chouinard's art here to contaminate the public.
