Walking through the mud, jungle and across rivers to offer free medical care
Dr Georges Bwelle provides free healthcare in Cameroon's villages
Dr. Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend seeing hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in this West African country, barely one in every 5,000 inhabitants.
Vote here or on your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 CNN Heroes of the Year 2013.
You can vote for him, or one of the 10 other heroes, to elect him CNN Hero of the Year.
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and visit hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one arm broken, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma that would carry the aftermath for the rest of his life.
 There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon , said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying her father to crowded clinics and hospitals, so that he could get any treatment he could benefit from.
 It is not easy , Mr Bwelle adds.
You can leave home at 5:00, rush to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor for 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not afford the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three quarters of the country's healthcare spending is made in the private sector.
 The only problem they have is poverty , Dr Bwelle explained.
And because of poverty, they can't enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his fellow countrymen suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed more than 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the central hospital in Yaoundé.
And he created a nonprofit humanitarian organization, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, they and about 30 others pile up in vans after they have fixed the medical equipment on the roof and cross rough terrain to reach the villages that need the most help.
Luck doesn't always follow them.
They had to push their vehicles to cross rivers or muddy tracks many times.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as heroes: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best accommodation available.
In these villages, free healthcare is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr Bwelle  with his big smile and his overflowing energy  is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team starts receiving hundreds of patients.
 We receive 500 people each visit, Mr Bwelle said.
Sometimes they live 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
This traveling hospital provides a variety of health care services.
Many people are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive candy, a pair of collected glasses or a free birth certificate  a document necessary to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford it.
In the evening, the team performs simple surgical procedures under local anesthesia.
The operation is usually performed in a school, town hall, or home; after the operation, the patient rises and goes to the wake room to leave room for the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a grueling rhythm, but the village musicians usually help the band stay motivated.
 They're playing drums all night to keep us awake so we can keep working , Mr Bwelle explained.
On Sunday, the team goes back to town, tired but proud of the work they've done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, performed 700 free surgeries last year, and they know that their presence can make a big difference for those they help.
One man explained that the free surgery he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
 It will change my future and that of my family , the man said.
In addition to running this itinerant hospital and working as a hospital surgeon, Dr Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
He explains that 60% of his association's funding comes from this second job, the rest from private donations.
"I don't know when he's sleeping", said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He's still in the hospital or trying to raise money for his association so he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr Bwelle in his missions, it is an opportunity to learn in the field that they do not have at home.
 We may have participated in operations to help sponge the blood or to pass the instruments to Dr. Bwelle , Ms. O'Malley explained.
It's not something you get the chance to do in America when you're a second-year medical student.
Volunteer students usually pay for their travel to Cameroon, often arriving with medical supplies.
But once in Yaoundé, their boarding house, transportation and education are taken care of by Dr Bwelle.
"He's a hero, there's no doubt about it", Katie O'Malley said.
He gave his life for this association, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is not going to go out.
For Dr Bwelle, relatively constant workload is not a problem.
Helping others live happily by keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him great joy.
 I am so happy when I do this work , Mr Bwelle added.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons I do this.
Please visit the ASCOVIME website to see how you can help.
